          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Iran is pointing fingers</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Iran’s Supreme Leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, is <a href="https://www.euronews.com/2024/12/11/iran-blames-us-and-israel-for-bashar-al-assads-fall-from-power-in-syria" target="_blank">accusing</a> the United States and Israel of being responsible for the collapse of Bashar al-Assad’s government in Syria. Khamenei claims to have “evidence” supporting these allegations and that there was no room for any doubt. He also suggested that a neighboring country played a significant role. However, he didn’t specify which neighbor. However, deductive reasoning would imply that it is likely <a href="https://www.cfr.org/expert-brief/what-role-turkey-playing-syrias-civil-war" target="_blank">Turkey</a>, as Turkey has been heavily involved in Syria.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">The US, Israel, and Turkey have had a hand in backing various Syrian proxies and have engaged in <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2024/dec/09/israel-us-and-turkey-launch-strikes-to-protect-interests-in-syria" target="_blank">strikes</a> in Syria. Another explanation for Assad’s decline is that his main allies, Russia and Iran, <a href="https://news.sky.com/story/assad-fall-not-surprising-as-russia-and-iran-decided-to-throw-syria-under-the-bus-13269400" target="_blank">tied</a> up with their wars and conflicts, making their Syrian support a ‘low-cost operations’ effort. Russia, despite assisting with airstrikes, has worn thin with its war in Ukraine. Iran has been overly busy arming its proxies against Israel.</p>
        </mj-text>
