          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Why are Syria and Russia close?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopolitics.world/email/images/gp-dec-12-3.jpg" alt="Why are Syria and Russia close?" href="https://www.geopolitics.world" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Russia's and Syria's <a href="https://www.bbc.com/news/newsbeat-39554171" target="_blank">friendship</a> predates the Assad family regime. Russia and Syria became close allies after the Second World War for two main reasons: influence and military support. During the <a href="https://www.britannica.com/event/Cold-War" target="_blank">Cold War</a>, Syria was the Soviet’s hold on countering American/Western influence in the Middle East. Syria was a Soviet proxy in the Middle East. After the days of the Cold War, Syria is still Russia’s main ally in preventing American imperialism and Western intervention in the Middle East.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Russia also extended mutual military support. The Soviets had proper access to the Mediterranean Sea, which they wouldn’t have had otherwise. Even after the collapse of the Soviet Union, Syria’s Tartus port hosts Russia’s only naval base in the Mediterranean, giving Russia a strategic foothold to the sea that it wouldn’t have. In return, the Soviets or Russians have always provided Syria with military support in exchange for this base. Both countries also benefitted from each other economically as well.​</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Now, this relationship is up in the air with this regime change. How this relationship with the new regime change corresponds with Russia remains to be seen. If Russia is forced to <a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/12/10/nx-s1-5222349/how-the-fall-of-the-assad-regime-in-syria-may-impact-russia" target="_blank">withdraw</a> from its bases in Syria, it will lose a geostrategic ally and might end Putin’s ambitions in the Middle East.​</p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
